{"id":"san-luis-obispo-north-coast-byway","generatedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z","designation":"All-American Road","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"California State Route 1","revisionId":1362071117,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_State_Route_1"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_State_Route_1","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"California State Route 1\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_State_Route_1","revisionId":1362071117,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"}],"endpoints":null,"itinerary":[{"place":"California State Route 1 (start)","mileFromStart":0,"kind":"terminus","lat":35.81415,"lng":-121.36056,"seq":1,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"The drive begins here","toNextMi":3.9},{"place":"Scenic overlook","mileFromStart":3.9,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.7807,"lng":-121.33236,"seq":2,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.1},{"place":"Breaker Point","mileFromStart":4,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.77816,"lng":-121.33059,"seq":3,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.6},{"place":"Point Sierra Nevada","mileFromStart":4.6,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.77077,"lng":-121.32517,"seq":4,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":9.4},{"place":"Seal Point","mileFromStart":14,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.66458,"lng":-121.26167,"seq":5,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.1},{"place":"Elephant Seal Vista Point","mileFromStart":14.1,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.6635,"lng":-121.25845,"seq":6,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.2},{"place":"Elephant Seal Viewing Area","mileFromStart":14.3,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.66234,"lng":-121.25614,"seq":7,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":1},{"place":"Elephant Seals Vista Point","mileFromStart":15.3,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.65283,"lng":-121.24138,"seq":8,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":3.7},{"place":"View of Hearst Castle","mileFromStart":19,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.64172,"lng":-121.18011,"seq":9,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.4},{"place":"Vista Area","mileFromStart":19.4,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.63998,"lng":-121.17451,"seq":10,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":4.3},{"place":"Vista Pt","mileFromStart":23.7,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.59303,"lng":-121.1254,"seq":11,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.9},{"place":"Leffingwell Landing","mileFromStart":24.6,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.58071,"lng":-121.11814,"seq":12,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":13.5},{"place":"Estero Bay","mileFromStart":38.1,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.45116,"lng":-120.95098,"seq":13,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.6},{"place":"Cayucos Point","mileFromStart":38.7,"kind":"overlook","lat":35.44669,"lng":-120.94013,"seq":14,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":39.3},{"place":"California State Route 1 (end)","mileFromStart":78,"kind":"terminus","lat":35.44943,"lng":-120.92348,"seq":15,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"The drive ends here"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["SR 1 has become famous worldwide, but the highway was signed as several other routes prior to 1964. When the road was first envisioned in the World War I era, California highways were referred to by either a highway name or a route number. The route numbers were used by state highway planners and the Legislature from 1915 until 1964, but were never posted on highways, referred to by the auto clubs or public, nor used on maps. The SR 1 designation was first assigned in 1939. Various portions of SR 1 have been posted and referred to by various names and numbers over the years. State construction of what became SR 1 started after the state's third highway bond issue passed before 1910.","Eager for a direct coastal route between Ventura and Santa Barbara, civic boosters used locally raised funds to begin building the Rincon Sea Level Road in 1911. The route between the Ventura River and Carpinteria had been an unimproved route along small alluvial fan beaches that skirted coastal bluff rock outcroppings at low tide. Construction of the Southern Pacific Coast Line railroad had created a road flanked by riprap along this area. In order to make this part of the first coastal route for motorists driving from San Francisco to Los Angeles, they paved the road and built wooden causeways where the route flooded from the ocean waves. Local funding ran out, but the newly formed State Highway Commission took over and completed the road in 1913.","One of the most difficult routes to build was along the Big Sur coast. The state first approved building Route 56, or the Carmel-San Simeon Highway, to connect Big Sur to the rest of California in 1919. Federal funds were appropriated and in 1921 voters approved additional state funds. San Quentin State Prison set up three temporary prison camps to provide unskilled convict labor to help with road construction. One was set up by Little Sur River, one at Kirk Creek and a third was later established in the south at Anderson Creek. Inmates were paid 35 cents per day and had their prison sentences reduced in return. The route necessitated construction of 33 bridges, the largest of which was the Bixby Bridge. Six more concrete arch bridges were built between Point Sur and Carmel.","After 18 years of construction, aided by New Deal funds during the Great Depression, the paved two-lane road was completed and opened on June 17, 1937. The road was initially called the Carmel-San Simeon Highway (Route 56), but was better known as the Roosevelt Highway, honoring the current President Franklin D. Roosevelt. A 1921 law extended Route 56 south over the county road to Cambria."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"The state has relinquished, and turned over various segments of the highway to local control.","url":""},{"n":2,"text":"Indicates that the postmile represents the distance along US 101 rather than SR 1.","url":""},{"n":3,"text":"Exit numbers follow US 101 rather than SR 1.","url":""},{"n":4,"text":"Indicates that the postmile represents the distance along I-280 rather than SR 1.","url":""},{"n":5,"text":"Exit numbers follow I-280 rather than SR 1.","url":""},{"n":6,"text":"Although the southbound exit to John Daly Boulevard is listed as exit 511 on Caltrans' exit number list, as of 2025[update] signs on the highway were posted marking it as exit 49, following I-280 instead of SR 1/","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=California_State_Route_1&action=edit"},{"n":7,"text":"California Department of Transportation. \"State Truck Route List\". Sacramento: California Department of Transportation. Archived from the original (XLS file) on September 5, 2015. Retrieved June 30, 2015.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20150905083346/http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/traffops/trucks/truckmap/truck-route-list.xlsx"},{"n":8,"text":"\"Special Route Restrictions\". California Department of Transportation. Archived from the original on September 12, 2014. Retrieved July 25, 2014.","url":"http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/traffops/engineering/trucks/routes/restrict-list.htm"}],"routeLine":[[35.81415,-121.36056],[35.81463,-121.35997],[35.81518,-121.35955],[35.81567,-121.35913],[35.81526,-121.35859],[35.8146,-121.35889],[35.81379,-121.35888